    {
      "id": "about-twilite-reader",
      "type": "port",
      "label": "About Twilite Reader",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": -520,
        "y": -1440
      },
      "width": 320,
      "height": 210,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-about-twilite"
        },
        "view": {
          "intent": "node",
          "payload": "node.web.detail"
        },
        "renderShape": {
          "kind": "markdown"
        },
        "markdown": "# About Twilite\n---\n\nThis lesson explains what kind of system Twilite is, how it wants you to think about graphs, and why the project keeps pulling authoring, runtime, and publishing into the same web-shaped space."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "about-twilite-intro",
      "type": "tutorial-title",
      "label": "Lesson Hero",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": -180,
        "y": -1100
      },
      "width": 620,
      "height": 260,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "About Twilite",
        "subtitle": "Twilite is not just a graph editor or a document system. It is trying to make graphs the native shape of authoring, navigation, rendering, and eventually public web software.",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-title",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-title.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-title.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-title",
          "classRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-title.node-class.node"
        },
        "definitionKey": "tutorial-title",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-about-twilite"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "about-twilite-graph-native-note",
      "type": "tutorial-concept",
      "label": "Graph-Native",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": -760,
        "y": -520
      },
      "width": 360,
      "height": 240,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "Graphs Are The Native Medium",
        "body": "Twilite wants nodes, edges, ports, portals, surfaces, and declarations to be first-class working material. The graph is not just a diagram of the system. It is the system’s authoring shape.",
        "tag": "Concept",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-concept",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-concept",
          "classRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "definitionKey": "tutorial-concept",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-about-twilite"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "about-twilite-web-note",
      "type": "tutorial-concept",
      "label": "Web System",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": -300,
        "y": -520
      },
      "width": 360,
      "height": 240,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "The Web Is The Convergence Layer",
        "body": "Twilite keeps moving toward a model where public graphs, runtime surfaces, navigation, and application behavior all come together on the web. That is why GitHub-backed graphs and browser-facing surfaces matter so much here.",
        "tag": "Concept",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-concept",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-concept",
          "classRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "definitionKey": "tutorial-concept",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-about-twilite"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "about-twilite-moving-note",
      "type": "tutorial-concept",
      "label": "Still Moving",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": 160,
        "y": -520
      },
      "width": 360,
      "height": 240,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "The Ontology Is Ahead Of The Product In Some Places",
        "body": "Twilite already has a strong model, but not every part of the product is equally mature yet. Some systems are clean and live today; others are still being worked into the runtime and public authoring experience.",
        "tag": "Concept",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-concept",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-concept",
          "classRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "definitionKey": "tutorial-concept",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-about-twilite"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "about-twilite-example",
      "type": "tutorial-example",
      "label": "Reading Lens",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": 640,
        "y": -520
      },
      "width": 400,
      "height": 240,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "Reading Lens",
        "body": "Use the checklist below when you are trying to understand whether a Twilite graph is teaching the ontology, showing a workflow, or acting as a real runtime surface.",
        "cta": "Inspect the lens",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-example",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-example.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-example.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-example",
          "classRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-example.node-class.node"
        },
        "definitionKey": "tutorial-example",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-about-twilite"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "about-twilite-lens-note",
      "type": "markdown",
      "label": "How To Read Twilite",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": 640,
        "y": -120
      },
      "width": 430,
      "height": 340,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-about-twilite"
        },
        "markdown": "## How to read Twilite\n\n1. Ask whether this graph is teaching a concept, guiding a workflow, or acting as a real application surface.\n2. Look for the declaration, exposed surfaces, and navigation model.\n3. Treat nodes as authored meaning, not just boxes on a canvas.\n4. Expect some parts of the ontology to feel more complete than the current public runtime.\n5. Read the tutorials as both instruction and evidence of the model.\n\nTwilite usually makes more sense when you ask what role a graph is playing."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "about-twilite-challenge",
      "type": "tutorial-challenge",
      "label": "Challenge",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": 1140,
        "y": -120
      },
      "width": 360,
      "height": 220,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "Challenge",
        "body": "1. Open a tutorial graph.\n2. Explain whether it is acting mainly as a concept lesson, a workflow guide, or a runtime-facing surface.\n3. Point to the declaration and the exposed surface that support your answer.",
        "difficulty": "starter",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-challenge",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-challenge.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-challenge.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-challenge",
